  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own community. Growing up in a small Italian town where my parents both had limited formal education, I learned early that your background could shape how others see your potential. Now, as a barista in Naples, I've noticed how students from similar backgrounds often feel pressure when they enter STEM fields. The stereotype that 'girls aren't good at math' or 'people from my region aren't cut out for engineering' isn't just a myth—it's a real barrier. It's not about innate ability; it's about the fear of confirming a stereotype that's been repeated so many times it becomes self-fulfilling. I think we absolutely should address it, but the way we do it matters. Instead of focusing on fixing the students' skills, we need to build environments where they feel safe to make mistakes. In my daily life, I see how important it is to create spaces where people aren't judged for their 'lack' of confidence. For example, when I work with customers who are nervous about their math skills, I focus on their strengths rather than their weaknesses. The solution isn't about changing the curriculum or the tests—it's about changing the culture around learning. We need to normalize the idea that everyone has the capacity to learn, especially those who might feel they don't belong. It's a small shift in perspective that can have a huge impact.",
